body:
Two minor init/utility bugs:

### 1. Unchecked PyModule_AddObject for 6 exception classes

`kiwisolver.cpp:132-137` calls `PyModule_AddObject` for all 6 exception classes without checking return values. On failure, the module loads in a broken state (exceptions missing from namespace), and the reference semantics are wrong (`PyModule_AddObject` steals on success only).

```cpp
PyModule_AddObject( mod, "DuplicateConstraint", DuplicateConstraint );
PyModule_AddObject( mod, "UnsatisfiableConstraint", UnsatisfiableConstraint );
// ... 4 more, all unchecked
```

Since the minimum version is 3.10, `PyModule_AddObjectRef` is available and has cleaner semantics (never steals):

```cpp
if( PyModule_AddObjectRef( mod, "DuplicateConstraint", DuplicateConstraint ) < 0 )
    return false;
// ...
```

### 2. Solver_dump passes NULL to PyObject_Print

`solver.cpp:236-237` — if `PyUnicode_FromString` fails (OOM or bad UTF-8 from kiwi), `dump_str` is NULL and `PyObject_Print(NULL, stdout, 0)` crashes.

```cpp
cppy::ptr dump_str( PyUnicode_FromString( dumps.c_str() ) );
// Missing: if (!dump_str) return 0;
PyObject_Print( dump_str.get(), stdout, 0 );
```

Both are one-line fixes.

Found by [cext-review-toolkit](https://github.com/devdanzin/cext-review-toolkit).
